  "business_context": "Email-message records hold the actual content and routing metadata of every email that touches the CRM. They differ from generic Activity entries in that they carry email-specific structured data: From / To / CC / BCC addresses, the HTML and plaintext body, RFC-822 Message-ID for thread reconciliation, In-Reply-To references, and a direction flag (Sent / Received). Modeling varies: Salesforce has EmailMessage as a separate object distinct from Task; HubSpot has Email as an Engagement subtype; EspoCRM has Email as its own first-class entity (with rich threading support); CiviCRM has Activity records with activity_type_id=Email and additional Email Activity Type fields; Bloomerang has Interaction subtype=Email; Attio syncs emails from Gmail / Outlook via OAuth and surfaces them on Person and Company timelines without a separate first-class Email entity. Email-to-record auto-association (BCC the CRM's catch-all address; the email is logged against any contact/account whose email matches a recipient) is the most common automation tied to email records. When interviewing clients, surface \"Email\" by asking how they currently log email correspondence with contacts: do they manually log it, do they BCC a catch-all CRM address, do they use an integrated mail client (Gmail / Outlook plugin), or does they rely on a marketing-platform integration?",
